This project implements Morpheus.dev, a visual mock-backend builder for developers.

The system allows users to define database schemas (tables, fields, relationships) through a UI, generate realistic mock data, and automatically expose REST API endpoints that behave like a real backend.

The architecture is split into two core layers:
1. Metadata layer (PostgreSQL): stores project definitions, schema, relationships, and endpoint configuration.
2. Runtime layer (SQLite per project): stores generated data and serves API requests.

The backend dynamically compiles user-defined schemas into SQL, generates runtime databases, and exposes endpoints such as:
- GET /runtime/:project/:table
- GET /runtime/:project/:table/:id
- POST /runtime/:project/:table

The frontend is a React + TypeScript application used to:
- create and manage projects
- define schema visually
- generate and preview data
- view and consume endpoints

Key constraints:
- schema is the source of truth
- no direct SQL input from users
- runtime data must be isolated per project
- endpoints must be generated automatically from schema

The MVP must support:
- tables and fields
- mock data generation
- basic relationships (one-to-many)
- GET and POST endpoints

Do not implement advanced features (auth rules, GraphQL, exports, etc.) until core functionality is stable.

