# 16. Relationship Rules

## 16.1 MVP Relationship Support
Support:
- one-to-one
- one-to-many
- many-to-one

Do not support direct many-to-many as a first-class visual pattern in MVP.

## 16.2 Many-to-Many Later
Handle many-to-many later via explicit join tables.

## 16.3 Relationship Constraints
For MVP:
- only allow foreign keys to target primary keys
- enforce compatible data types
- generate parent rows before child rows
- prevent circular generation dependencies for v1

---

# 17. Endpoint Strategy

## 17.1 Runtime Endpoint Format
Suggested runtime API format:

```text
GET    /runtime/:projectSlug/:tableSlug
GET    /runtime/:projectSlug/:tableSlug/:id
POST   /runtime/:projectSlug/:tableSlug
```

Example:

```text
GET    /runtime/demo-shop/users
GET    /runtime/demo-shop/users/123
POST   /runtime/demo-shop/orders
```

## 17.2 Builder API Format
Separate builder and runtime APIs completely.

Example builder routes:

```text
POST   /api/projects
GET    /api/projects/:projectId
POST   /api/projects/:projectId/tables
PATCH  /api/tables/:tableId
POST   /api/tables/:tableId/fields
PATCH  /api/fields/:fieldId
POST   /api/projects/:projectId/relationships
POST   /api/projects/:projectId/generate
GET    /api/projects/:projectId/endpoints
```

## 17.3 Endpoint Operations in MVP
Auto-generate:
- list endpoint
- get by id endpoint
- create endpoint

## 17.4 Deferred Operations
Later:
- update endpoint
- delete endpoint
- filtering
- sorting
- pagination
- custom routes
- nested routes

